\begin_body

\begin_layout Subsection
Automatic sentiment analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extract the sentiment of news articles using a lexicon based algorithm
 in the line of Taboada (2011).
 The software for the implementation is the qdap package (see Rinker, 2013)
 in the open Software project R (see R Core Team, 2013).
 Each word is compared to a lexicon of positive and negative words, such
 as “bad”, “detrimental” and “dangerous” (negative), respectively “good”,
 “beneficial” and “safe” (positive).
 The sentiment values are based on the lexicon SentimentWortschatz, or SentiWS
 for short (see Remus et al., 2010).
 The latter is a publicly available German-language resource for sentiment
 analysis.
 It contains positive and negative sentiment bearing words weighted within
 the interval of [1; 1] plus their part of speech tag, and if applicable,
 their inflections.
 The version employed here (SentiWS v1.8b) contains 1,650 negative and 1,818
 positive words, which sum up to 16,406 positive and 16,328 negative word
 forms, respectively.
 It contains adjectives and adverbs as well as nouns and verbs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before the values are summed up, valence shifters are accounted for.
 First, negativity is accounted for by inverting the value of a sentiment
 word in the lexicon if it is preceded by a negator.
 For example, the negator “no” inverts the originally positive value of
 “good”.
 Then, amplifiers like “very” and de-amplifiers like “less” are employed
 to increase or decrease the respective values.
 A context cluster of words is pulled from around this polarized word (
 4 words before and 2 words after) to be considered as valence shifters.
 containing a comma before the polarized word will only consider words found
 after the comma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each article is attributed an sentiment value, 
\begin_inset Formula $ArticleValue$
\end_inset

, defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ArticleValue=\frac{\Sigma_{j}^{N}wordvalue_{j}\times n_{j}}{N},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

